<dl id="n53050k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53050k">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53050k"> 50(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> langeweile</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>Langeweile</mark> (boredom, tedium)]: <font color="green">[Language cannot create time concepts &mdash; spatial terms are needed to qualify time &hellip; Anyway, this linguistic usage is so old and so general that we do not notice the metaphor any more when, for example, we use the word &lsquo;long&rsquo; to denote a certain length of time. [Thus in the word &lsquo;Langeweile&rsquo;]</font> &lsquo;Lang&rsquo; denotes a spatial dimension, and only in the second instance a temporal dimension. &hellip; &lsquo;Weile&rsquo; (while) is related to Old Norse words for rest (<i>hvild</i>) and originally denoted &lsquo;the resting place&rsquo; &hellip;] <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 125</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Right margin </mm> </dd></dl>
